The Ukrainian parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted in the framework of the amendment of the Criminal Code.
The amendment, which would open the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-prime minister, the MPs rejected in the second reading of the proposal to ease the penalties for economic crimes.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for signing a allegedly unfavorable gas contract with Russia.
The verdict is not final, the appeal of the convicted is due to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko describes the verdict as a political revenge of the regime, suspicion of the court’s bias has triggered the trial in the West.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 deputies.
