The diet of an obese child: does not eat breakfast and dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, with overweight 9 percent of schoolchildren and obese 5 percent of children.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to a recent survey.
Again, it shows how important the environment in which he grows and the patterns with which he is surrounded are for the healthy development of a person.
For example, on tables in obese children, smoking occurs up to half as often as in families of children with a normal weight.
Strawberries had to dinner the day before a research-related awareness event called Obesity is not a coincidence for more than 19 percent of obese.
In families with obesity, it is also unusual to play sports, but this applies to most families of today’s schoolchildren – only 15 percent of children responded that their parents would find time for active exercise at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children from elementary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of the Obesity is not a coincidence event, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 students from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Proper nutrition and sufficient movement in the family is one of the determining factors that causes the dramatically rising number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"Only half of those surveyed said they ate five times a day in the breakfast-sweat-lunch-sweat-dinner mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," the study said.
No Breakfast and Evening
Experts point out that for healthy development are important and relative details, including the regular time of family breakfast.
Only 23% of schoolchildren eat breakfast at the same time.
Most families eat breakfast on their own.
And the worst was the finding that one in ten households did not eat at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The survey showed that in families with obese children, unhealthy chips are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
Regularly, more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, but their parents had less than half the result - 15 percent.
Set up your dining table
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to build their own diets from the offered options according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes are lots of flour, meat and sweet dishes.
"Alarming is especially the high popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report of the survey states.
For lunch, the main meal was pasta over poultry.
Children, however, practically didn’t want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetable dishes is low.
Tender to Health
The survey also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they are given the right information.
“In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the awareness lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, there was in a number of cases a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition,” the project results state.
This is especially true in the case of sweet lemonade, where more children would prefer regular water.
Children were also much more likely to check out poultry and fish in the questionnaire as the main meal of the day and would restrict sweet foods and knobs.
