Need for Speed: The Run races across America.
Recensions
Originally, the careless ride turns into a routine morning trip to the shift due to a series of completely unnecessary laidback mistakes.
The ambition has largely been fulfilled, but it is not valid when nobody obviously wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode, titled The Run, had high expectations before it was released.
He promised that the long-standing racing series of Need for Speed would once again move in a new direction, and from the playable shows he appeared as a game that would not have to be counted in the genre of action racing.
We were also curious how the inserted passages, in which the main character will get out of the car and go on his way.
As with the NFS series, it is customary, many results are a little different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have appeared in the series more or less for several years.
So this is actually not even a mistake, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are brought into a story whose protagonist Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You sit behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea brings with it a few interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race runs on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t have the feeling that the game is always the same.
Some of the environments are also very nice to see, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
This is nothing worldly.
But riding across the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains is visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are spotted from time to time with some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you will get into a sandstorm, which greatly reduces visibility.
In the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught by a lava.
In addition, the individual races are well arranged.
There are only a few types, but that is enough.
For a while, you try to outperform the desired number of opponents (in essence, a classic race), then you catch up with the time (a classic match with a stopper) and then you are waiting for a duel with a single opponent.
From time to time, the police are also involved in this, which makes your efforts even more frustrating.
There are passages outside the car.
It’s more about such interactive animations, where Jack mostly runs away from someone and you have to help him in this by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, there are far fewer passages in the game than you would expect (per only three).
As a result, this is to the benefit of the thing, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the aforementioned it is so ranked among the elements that spread the game.
The driving model follows the tracks of the previous parts.
That is, it is definitely not known nowadays, but it cannot be said that it would be a negative.
If you’re looking for a realistic simulation, you’ll have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-conscious racing model still suits quite well, even though we could find better at the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the model, the collision model is no longer very good.
From the game of this type, we do not expect to count complex deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how your car will behave before any impact on any object, then probably not everything is fine.
Typically, when you close ahead or bypass cars in regular traffic, you sometimes only slightly lick each other, but other times in a identical situation your car ends up in wild piruets.
Or even directly.
Thanks to the restart system, it does not bother, but it will break you reliably.
Restarts are resolved in such a way that if you break up or get out of the track, the game throws you back to the last point on the track.
Only five restarts are available in each race.
Once you have exhausted them, you have to start the race from the beginning.
It is therefore more such a help in the event that something does not work, than that you could rely on them explicitly.
Sometimes even restarts do not help, solving them up to the need to learn a given section of the race to remember.
The big drawback of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some turns, for example, need to be done in a specific way, otherwise you will not get into them.
Other times you will encounter “civil” cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying when you see the opponent easily pass between two opposing cars before you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to circumvent or brake them.
It doesn’t matter when you get to them, because it’s “calculated” so that the situation is always right before your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
Thro the game, you will encounter several locations where, regardless of time, the same opponent will always outperform you in the same place.
This is most important at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
The enemy must get there before you obviously at any cost.
When it runs in front of you, it makes the overview of opposite cars worse, so you start off there a few times.
You can understand the intention of making the game more thrilling and adrenaline-like, but the execution is so obvious that it reliably quickly discourages you.
And it’s a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and in places even so actionful that sometimes you literally don’t get to watch where it’s flying.
And it doesn’t really matter if the concept with fifty unique tracks is worth it, whether it is to sort races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance, or anything else.
It’s an unusual idea to change cars during races.
You have to be careful about gas pumps on the roads, because you can change the car there, although in the vast majority of cases you will get enough of what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports are suitable for urban areas, strong American railroads for straight highways and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example, on cliffy mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you gain not only medals, but also experience points into your profile, which is common for challenges and story.
To gain a higher level of driver, various objects are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with the backgrounds for the profile.
It is also connected with the online Autolog feature, which, among other things, compares your achievements with other players and provides additional community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand tricks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you will get to the metro tunnel (budiž), where you will drive it in the dark on the rails (budiž).
On the tachometer, the numbers blink between 150 and 200 km/h (by the way), and in this, the subway set will be attached from the back and will uncompromisingly scratch you.
In the editorial, we will probably have a discussion for a few days about whether when creating the game nobody really did not think a little, or whether the authors think of us as really such a big fool.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It is so frightening that in some more intense moments the shooting decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
This applies, however, primarily to the bullshit with a greater number of participants, when a smooth shooting would no longer be valid.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category "every dog is different", but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, the game will probably not be bought.
Need for Speed: The Run is a big deal.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we’t be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS game of the last few years.
This is how the game works outright.
Fun is definitely fine, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will shake you in the eye with the power of airport reflectors.
