Ambassador to the EU Vicenová:
The Czechs have a reputation of negativists and eurosceptics
“The Lisbon Treaty has significantly disrupted the balance between the various institutions.”
“I didn’t expect it to be such a tough war.”
"It will take five, six years before the situation settles a little, calms down and before all players get used to their new roles," Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicen said.
How seriously she takes her motto "Understandably and openly about Europe", she showed in the first part of the lecture, when she managed to describe the individual EU institutions and their relations in such a clear and comprehensible way that she could be envious by a number of lecturers from the UK Law School.
Vicen also praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council Herman Van Rompuy:
“First of all, there was criticism that he was insignificant, that he was a grey official, that he couldn’t play any role, and I have to say that everyone was breathtaking, that he performed well in that role.”
