There are many factors to blame, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivation letters, but also the low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
“Believe me, when a Polish and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak comes to me, the Frenchman next to me will say, ‘Hey, what do you meet there, what about your Visegrad four?’ and he doesn’t look enthusiastic about it at all.”
In the future, the EU, according to Vicen, mainly awaits new tough rules for budgetary policies of member countries.
He then sees the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe, rather than a new “European federation” as very real.
“There are countries in the euro area and countries outside the euro area.”
“We have the Schengen area, we have the institute of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it was said that only countries that want to cooperate and those that don’t want to stay away.”
“These institutions will be more and it will be a strong two-speed Europe,” Vicen expects.
In this regard, she also appreciated the role played by the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the principle that all issues affecting the Union as a whole should be discussed between all Member States, not just between the euro area countries.
Brand story:
IBM begins the second century of its existence
If someone were to look for the word that most accurately describes IBM’s strategy, the closest one would probably be “long-term”.
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet it has been a hundred years since its founding.
The foundation of this long term was laid by the company’s first CEO, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He said that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan “Think!” became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine that began to appear at IBM in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson’s carefully built corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained faithful to its core values and was not afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope we can even more in the second hundred,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the current CEO of the company.
SOFTWARE SYSTEM
In the 1930s, Watson approached caring for his employees in the same way as entrepreneur Baťa did in the Czech Republic – IBM employees were among the first Americans to have paid leave, employer insurance plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system to reward the best inventors and merchants.
IBM has a long-standing relationship with its customers.
The company has been brilliant in talent harvesting from the outset – being one of the world’s first companies to eliminate any discrimination so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is that Palmisana will be replaced next year by a woman, Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for 30 years and still holds the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been making so-called jams, online brainstormings, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
