IBM History: From a Cheese Cutter to Space Flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a century ago, originally under the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was first adopted in 1924 as a brand used by the company’s branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for later IBM was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They owned technologies such as the famous “pistols,” which are clocks that record the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, a businessman who also chaired the company’s supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a competitive firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him manage the company.
The leader then overshadowed IBM’s founder – Watson’s ideas have built an unbeatable corporate culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name implies, began with the manufacture and sale of all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese cutting machines to cash machines.
During the first four years of Watson’s leadership, the company’s turnover doubled to $9 million and the company expanded to all continents.
Watson was so important to the company that he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior, after almost forty years in the chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, humans and computers from IBM helped NASA steer flights into space - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight of man to the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360.
The IBM 5150 was introduced to the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to Lenovo, bought the consultancy division of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began dedicating itself fully to consultancy and value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, a "smarter planet".
Its aim is to use technology intelligently in areas not yet planned and to improve the situation, for example, in transportation or city management.
For the area of commerce, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which helps marketers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country.
She established her branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-class voice recognition research team.
