How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the majority of travel agencies sold only tours to the countries of the Socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both on the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned to the West and Czech tourists' journeys to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually, even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand the front overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for trips to the West, was not given to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the trip to the West.
Most often, however, the Czechs spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of houses and chalets that the Czechs purchased and this custom still exists today.
Czech travel has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 vacation in the NDR or Bulgaria was our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox, which we do not realize today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to Croatia, which is currently the most popular for us, until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
At the end of the 1990s, the abolition of the visa requirement for neighboring Western European countries started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria’s Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks were not able to take a trip to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
In Paris, for example, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of the travel of the Czechs at this time was driving their own food, canned food, salads, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after many decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living, and with it, average wages, however, rose, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have begun to regularly prepare tours with charter airlines since 1997, thus air travel thanks to the possibility to obtain quantitative discounts compared to the past have grown incredibly low.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all developed countries of the world, except for the United States, which continued to make our travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when the first historically direct charter flight to exotic Thailand was delivered from the Czech Republic due to considerable demand.
From this year on, every year they fly with Czech tourists direct charters to warm distant countries, this winter it will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit these exotic countries annually.
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visas for Czech tourists and thus our country definitively ranked among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person for one overseas vacation including costs at the place of residence.
