Massacre on a Personal Level
Peter Englund’s emotional new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with such a long list of outstanding characters as to turn your head out of it.
One advice to keep up at the moment: Carefully remove this page and make it a bookmark.
With all the people you will be very well acquainted in Mr. Englund’s novel narrative and this list will serve as a navigation – like a kind of beacon – in the moments when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a member of the Swedish Academy, which is awarding the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual – the author himself describes it, quite accurately, as “anti-historical work.”
It contains several very well-known names, important contracts and famous battles, but it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and tactics and equipment discussions.
It’s not a book about what happened, the author explains, but rather “a book about what it was.”
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the war experiences of 20 more and fewer men and women on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, emergency drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others will become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives are flaming like the flames of candles lit in the church – new ones are added to the plot of fate, while others are extinguished.
The book of Mr. Englund differs from classical historical novels.
It modifies the notion that the First World War was only about horrendous canyon battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve the problems of falling bee nests on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids, or struggling with the presence of tse-tse flies.
It was a very exciting reading from the beginning.
War will sweep people’s lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smells like gun dust.
When the shooting starts in the distance and you are the woman who is at home with her children, will you run away or stay?
Who is actually approaching?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was unleashed.
“The vacuum created by the lack of facts,” noted Mr. Englund, “was filled with guesses, assumptions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian Army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are taken from biographies, letters and other materials already published.
The descriptions of their lives may sound frightening and engaging, but thanks to the incorporation of tiny moments and details they are absolutely vivid and credible.
Many of them talk about suffering and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "The victims, the substitutes everywhere."
"Coffee imitation, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in sheep fat (and supplemented with fake bone from wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato shells, shoes with wooden pants".
It mentions that there were “837 registered meat substitutes in the production of strawberries and 511 registered coffee substitutes.”
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American finds in himself an inner urge to be wild and brutal, and declares about war, “You will finally understand that this is human nature. Not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whisky, evening newspapers or a good book and pretend that this mask represents civilization and that there is no barbaric behind that scratched self.”
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely soon die, and no one will notice it, let alone to mourn.
“When one finally accepts to sacrifice, he would at least expect it to happen in front of the eyes of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “condemned man who is secretly hanged.”
Other notes relate to the departure of the old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
“The conflict became increasingly economic competition and competitive struggle,” writes Mr. Englund, “war between factories.”
He captured what he calls “a new kind of beast of the coming century: a pronounced and ideologically sworn mass murderer in custom-cut clothes, who performs his bloodshed without rising from the table.”
People behave completely unexpectedly, madness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a sexual illness from prostitutes in order to avoid service on the front.
“The most grotesque example of this behavior was the trade in gonococcal pus, which soldiers bought and sprayed on their genitals in the hope that it would end up in the hospital,” he writes.
“The most desperate people wiped it in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives.”
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund’s prose is quick, but not spectacular, which fits greatly to his human theme.
