After the tragedy this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
It’s easy – just go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t really that hard at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the British research team on European digital populism.
The stockpile of personal information on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that it was enough for researchers to simply take advantage of advertising on sites to determine the demographic group they were looking for with absolute accuracy – something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team across Europe found half a million right-wing fans, and then focused their attention on them and sent them ads. But instead of inviting them to a newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they asked them to fill out a questionnaire with questions about their level of education, their attitude to violence and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans from 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without having to leave the office at all.
“It’s an entirely new way of conducting research,” notes Bartlett.
Some of the findings are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are all young men, who are upset by the growing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of researchers.
Research teams, health scientists and policy researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends hidden by status updates, posts on the walls, and “Like” buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them daily on average provides three different data, making this social network literally a "information supernova", which is worth the development of many new research. The number of academic papers in whose name the word Facebook appears has increased from the state five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook lies in giving them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"In the past it was true that when you wanted to conduct a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to get into a party where you’d never be allowed,” says Bartlett.
“This is all Facebook breaks down – you just go straight to them.”
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that university students who dismantled their drunk-outs on Facebook were much more at risk of a problem of alcoholism than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moren suggests that peers of students monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunk status.
“The problem cannot be solved unless you can diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moren and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise have no chance of discovering."
Facebook is constantly scanning the data of its users.
The site’s information team compiled statistics on the relationship status and Valentine’s Day, 2010 election participation, and the nation’s satisfaction rate (mainly using the information they had access to – supporters of internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available for research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is being tracked, whether they like it or not – in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, they need to provide the site with their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Researchers have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
“I think most users didn’t even think that researchers could look into their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using public Facebook walls of his students.
"When it came to them, they took it as if there was only information between them and their friends."
The question of methodology should also be considered.
Even with offline research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is not possible to verify how much of the information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, thinks that a pencil and a notebook are still the best possible tools to use in research.
“When you go into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” he says.
"Social research should be about society and social activities - and damn a lot of social activities are still taking place off-line."
