How to recognize a lie
A blatant look at recent newspaper headlines shows how serious and ubiquitous lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain has full hands of work with accusations of sexually harassing several women - both sides claim the other is lying.
Penn State University administrators were accused of false testimony when they tried to hide records that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling U.S. President Barack Obama with the microphone turned on that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie has destroyed entire careers and damaged the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made himself a fool by publishing information that was immediately disproved by undeniable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of abusing funds from his campaign to try to hide his non-marital relationship.
And nobody will ever forget the media circus that ran around Bill Clinton while lying during his second term in office about his sexual attraction to Monica Lewinsky.
Everywhere there are stories of fraud in school and at university.
There are instances when teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many fraud we encounter?
Studies have shown that in a single day you can find somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Let’s assume that many of them are mercy lies.
Another study revealed that strangers cracked three times during the first ten minutes of their first meeting in life.
Determining lies, or “recognizing lies”, is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar, say, to Sharadah, when one cries out, "I have you."Recognition of deception is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been disproved.
The liars are looking you in the eyes.
It’s not like they’re shaking, cocktailing, rubbing or shaving.
But don’t think it’s hard to detect and detect a liar.
A trained lies identifier can reveal the truth from the structure of sentences, small expressions in the face, the way questions are formed and their timing.
I’ve spent several years gathering scientific insights from the vast and growing industry of lying recognition and it’s clear that lying detection is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help in today’s complex world – especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, conducting interviews, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them be polished in vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men say more “self-centered” lies, while women say more lies “focused on others” – mostly to protect someone’s feelings – that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (although the lies they say most often tend to be “disgraceful”).
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others will feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called “initial observation.”
He will find out what to compare with later on.
Note the posture of the subject, his laughter, work with the voice.
You should know if someone is constantly tapping their feet so that you don’t wrongly accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then try to identify the clusters of false verbal and non-verbal behavior.
Take this as a warning sign, not as evidence of a lie.
People telling lies can stop moving their upper half of the body when trying to recall their fictional story, they can turn the tips of their shoes toward the door, lean toward the exit, significantly change their posture, or show "relief after the end of the conversation" - exaggerated relief breathing and changing positions when there is a difficult confession behind them.
People conducting interviews often give a false signal that the interview is over just to see what relief will look like after it is over.
Consider the language of the subject.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once rebuked and used past time to claim that his murdered woman was alive, which started a nationwide search for her body.
People who are lying may also say, “I didn’t have any sexual relationships with that lady... Mrs. Lewinsky,” or they will repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are only very minor.
Someone can use a lot of “diminishing language” when answering a difficult question: “Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to my best knowledge.”
In such a response, too many facts are not learned, and often it is another warning signal.
There is no magic by which every lie can be revealed, but it is possible to learn the skills by which the lie can be investigated.
Through these skills, a person will have a greater chance of not hitting a liar or deceiver in his personal and professional life.
