Climate change has hampered the economy
During the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdez, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment declined and with it the economy.
The year 2011 will enter the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the reign of Maria Lopez Valdez, who calls himself the Government of Change. This government brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth was recorded and there was even a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
The low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the possibilities of growth of the state economy, reduced economic activity by 3.6% in the first half of this year. In agriculture there was a historic decline of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to a report on damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78,03% was completely destroyed and on the remaining 21,07% partial damage was detected.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant rise in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state recorded an increased rise during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing a unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August, the average unemployment continued to grow and reached 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed. Compared to the first quarter, therefore, the number of unemployed increased by 18 969 people.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard Lopez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on steps taken at the level of public policy.
“We are witnessing rising unemployment related to various factors. These include, among other things, losing liquidity in the market due to resource constraints due to legislation passed by Congress in connection with anti-money laundering. For people who illegally seize dollars, it is not easy to earn, invest, or use them for something,” he stressed.
Stop migration
López Cervantes said that the demographic factor also contributes to the rise in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave for work abroad, to the United States, has decreased, both because of the difficult entry and then also because even if these people get beyond the border, it is difficult for them to find work.
Unreliability
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed population in the state works without paying benefits to the Social Security Administration.
Additional features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and unreliability.In this administrative territory, the lowest wages are from across the country, as by the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5,352 pessets as of September, well below the national average of 7,375 pessets.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, 2011 also saw the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance, in the period from January to June, foreign direct investment reached the amount of $630 697 which represents a decrease of 87.74% from the amount of $5,143 312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government reports investments in the amount of 17,280 million pessets per year.
debt
In connection with the economic downturn scenario, the state’s government asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos. This would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. Until November, no debt gains were recorded in any sector of the state’s economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Maria Lopez Valdés pointed out the lack of managerial capabilities of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, stated that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small during this year. We must work intensively to recover the land we lost this year. In 2012 we must double our efforts, there was a lack of harmonization of the efforts of all of us and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let us hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Slow economy
Loredo López said events such as the frost at the beginning of the year stopped the state’s economy and restricted its development and growth.
“The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including freezing. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to re-establish dynamics that would allow us to an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services.
Redefining the Mission
According to Theodore Salazar Uriarte, President of the Employers Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed toward more dynamic productive activities.
"Overall, we observe that it is working.We believe it is necessary to prepare a long-term plan in which the goals and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has," he said.
The work ahead of us
Chairman Coparmex stressed the importance of setting a vision of the future that would better guide the government’s efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to good results in various areas, there has been some progress in economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy leadership.
“There are elements that allow us to argue that the government is trying to be friendly.I can say that there is work done here and I think the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us,” he said.
