Court Approves "End of Analog Broadcasting" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) has rejected a constitutional lawsuit filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against a presidential decree that wants to speed up the so-called "analog signal shutdown" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juana Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing a decree outlining the individual steps that would lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
As a result, the Senate’s appeal was rejected because the qualified majority of eight votes needed for the Court to comment on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the aforementioned decree, which thus remains in force, was not reached.
The draft judgment drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero presents the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all issues relating to radio and television is a matter reserved by law to the Federal Commission for Telecommunications (Cofetel).
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Representatives supported the constitutional dispute in an effort to fight the decree.Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all actions described in it, leading to the transition to digitization.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the appeal filed by the House of Representatives, without entering into the discussion of the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not identify with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general standards measures to prepare the public administration.
"I don't think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," he said, adding that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital is one of the biggest changes the world has experienced in recent years.It is related to better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would mean delaying the benefits of digitalization, which requires decisions in the public interest, because digitalization is not only a technical dimension, but “it also affects economic, social, political and national security issues.”
As he stressed, these issues “require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state.
He recalled that a number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to the digital system and have done so through their governments, despite having highly specialized technical bodies at their disposal.
He stated that it is not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree, which to a certain extent interferes with the scope of Congress’s powers, to introduce in the sphere of administration the observance of laws prepared by the legislative power.
In Michoacán they analyze the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to data released by PREP, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's election is less than 27 percent.
The possibility of counting "vote by voice" appeared in this year's elections in Michoacán, where, according to data released by the Programme of Preliminary Election Results (PREP), the difference between the first and second seats in the governor's elections is less than 27 percent, and 879 votes out of a total of 6,074 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
In this context, the Chair of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacan (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral authority approved a series of measures that should harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not officially approve of its political constitution or its State Election Code or the Act on Electoral Justice, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral period had expired, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel neglected to publish them within the specified deadline in the Official State Gazette Act, having any objections to them.
On November 9, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislature and declared the head of state's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal" because it has no right to "neither approve nor veto".
Asked about the possibility of counting "vote by voice", María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the IEM General Council, it would be possible for the partial and total counting to be carried out by the local electoral authority.
In this way, the partial counting of the votes, of one or more electoral packages, will be possible under the following conditions: the election results do not agree; there is no record of the counting of the votes and the calculation in the appropriate box or it is not available to the President; or if there have been errors and obvious violations of the election results.
In addition, a total recalculation of votes in all polling stations will be possible if there is indication that the difference between the potential winner of the elections and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever at the beginning of the session there is an explicit request from the representative of the party and/or the coalition that has proposed the candidate in second place.
A total recalculation of the votes will also be possible if, after a proper recalculation, the difference between the likely winner and the second-place candidate is found to be equal to or less than one percentage point, and also whenever there is an explicit request from a political party whose candidate ended in the second place.
It should be mentioned that in such a situation are the elections in Morelia, where, according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second places is less than 0.16%, even though 129 of the total 923 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
