The new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that is keeping the country above the pit of an economic disaster.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that is keeping the country above the pit of an economic catastrophe and that has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The Presidential Palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgi Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to represent a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
“The framework is now well marked,” he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a much shorter time than usual.In the meantime, Italy is struggling to fight the political and financial crisis, which has caused the level of debt to rise to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve the tough package of austerity measures demanded by European leaders.
Due to market instability, interest rates on Italian 10-year bonds BTP have exceeded the 7 percent threshold, the level when Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, chairwoman of Italian employers’ organization Confindustria, told reporters after a meeting with Monti: “We said we will very much support this government.”
We believe this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this fierce situation.
Monti’s hopes for success were greatly increased thanks to the support of PDL’s Silvio Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts are predestined to good results,” Angelina Alfano, the secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant, as up to this point a number of its members opposed the government with a technocratic majority made up by Monti.
Support of Parliament
Monti’s new government needs strong parliamentary support to push for unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in this effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could mean a catastrophe.
Monti began talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women organisations.
The round of talks will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, which enabled a very quick move in response to the crisis.
After a short drop from the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, interest rates on Italian bonds have returned to a critical threshold, responding to uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will reap success.
Saving Italy, whose public debt amounts to 1.8 trillion euros, would be beyond the current euro zone financial reserves.
Monti said his government should remain in power until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will only give him time to carry out reforms and then call early elections.
Monti said he would like to incorporate politicians into his cabinet, but the big parties insist that this government must only be made up of experts to get Italy out of the hardships the country has come into due to financial pressure.
Political sources said mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicated the attempt to integrate political figures into the government.
