"Travel to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the band itself assures them that playing in Costa Rica is a dream fulfilled.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively to Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is on tour in South America to celebrate their 20th anniversary and will be on a unique stop in Central America on Sunday.
He will perform at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. together with the angel band The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is a sample from the interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the La Nación website on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a fulfilled dream. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
Traveling to Costa Rica is also our dream that becomes a reality.
We’ve been to South and Central America hardly a second time and the experience so far has been great.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation.It’s a wonderful country and I believe we’ll be able to stay here for a few days.
We are delighted to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally love the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your biggest supporters?
Thank you for standing with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica.Thank you for waiting so long and we’re sorry it took us so long.
Some people talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve shown in the last 21 years have taken place within a few weeks.
We had a few great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope to get in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We really look forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo.
My friends go surfing to Costa Rica or Nicaragua, or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. So we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love surfing.
Looking at your tour, you’ve prepared a great show with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played here, we don’t have any limitations on what we couldn’t do.
We will try to show the best show possible with a variety of songs.We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and diverse repertoire.
Never repeat the repertoire.
Why ?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 tracks and everyone likes different tracks, so it’s hard to choose what songs we’re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we have not played for a long time, we focus on them and are also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and so I think it is more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, it is.
First, I think no one of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much we have been given, and it impresses us that we can continue to play together.
We love and love to make music.
We are lucky to be able to see the places we have always wanted.
We could not have done better.
What meant for you that you were an important part of the formation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the great ones are represented.
The people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen too often.
From time to time a group is formed in a city, but it is far less common for five to ten groups to arise from one city at once.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with others.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We're lucky to be all our friends and it's an honor to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and have the same members even after those years.
Yes, we four have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly we are always interested in each other.
We’re all close friends and thanks to this we’ve managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we value each other’s music and I think it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy, however, thanks to your success you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
