Fujimori hospitalized for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday to be tested for muscle loss in the lower limbs, his doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who serves a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated four times and is currently under medical control.
Deputy Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Canal N television that Fujimori would undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days, where they should find out why he hurts and why he loses strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said he believes Fujimori could be granted grace for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself does not want grace because he feels innocent.
He was operated four times because of the cancer of the tongue, dropped 18 kilograms and added other problems such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has served in prison since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murder squadron of soldiers acting illegally in the first years of his reign.
