Park or mountain?
Architects gathered on the occasion of a draft procedure that brings with it more than polemics about fees
The 16 Gate City Contest once again opens the debate about the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the time of the greatest flourishing of the already extinct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The flyer defined the mountain as the big park of the metropolitan city of Barcelona.
Moreover, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York’s Central Park.
After the CMB disappeared in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper boundary of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that are not oriented on the axis north - south, but up (top) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild bears instead of the bear Yogi.
This was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega contest consisting of 16 calls for the same number of entrances to Collserola.
The gate of course captures the idea of the park.
Either this or someone is trying to place the gate on the field.
So the only question arises: Collserola, a park or a mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and based on a reflection on the city, this issue becomes the central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It’s already a topic as shaken as when two members of this old caste, elected at the meeting in the elevator, hand in hand.
And this was one of the rare coincidences between what three Barcelona architects and leading university professors thought.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the competition is justified.
According to Roldan, after the question of the Gulf Party was raised, "it is necessary" to discuss the "mountain side", so that Ildefonse Cerda's speech about green apples was not finished.
“We have to start from the principle that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its high availability.
Collserola is more complex," said the architect, for whom the name "the gates to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we must not imagine them "as entrances to the park, but rather as the definition of zones where it is possible to operate".
Modol, as well as Roldán and Bayona, with experience from the world of urbanism, qualifies the proposal as an “intellectual challenge” presenting “some dangers”.
The danger arising from the “uncertainty presented by the public space project today” after the experience of the 1980s, which had its “labyrinth singing” in the Forum area.
The first concern is the definition of the boundaries where it should be built.
“To define something is to take the next step,” that is to say, to move one step further.
"New urban planning and planning tools need to be kept in mind, as the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster."
If we focus on the question in more detail, Modol believes that the Collserola valley slope can be "considered a park", but not the Barcelona part, for purely topographic reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "should not end up in the garbage dump", although he welcomes the fact that the city council offers his gremio to intervene in the project from the "first moment".
And moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of leappoint that allows architects to engage in the debate, but he “doubts” that it should be precisely this technical profile that will lead multidisciplinary teams (“it’s all about skills,” he adds) that need to be created: “Architects should only be tools.”
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the name to this game is complicated because Collserola’s global vision is lacking in the procurement documents: “Sixteen procurements have been announced that deal with all the axes of the mountain – the sea, but there is no longitudinal study that would look at the area and understand it as a whole.”
This means that at least he has applied to all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the design of one gate can strike the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
According to him, the city council should ensure that the zone directly above the Ronda de Dalt should provide equipment throughout the zone to ensure a smooth transition between the city and the green.
