Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transportation (SCT) that the results of the investigation into the accident in which Prime Minister Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people were killed showed that the helicopter crashed directly to the ground with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary for Communications and Transportation, said that before the aircraft took off, the pilot stated that the weather conditions of the flight allowed.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, wings entangled in the branches of trees 25 meters from where the unit lost the body."
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, so it met all the requirements for the transportation of personnel.
In addition, he said that based on the investigation carried out in the impact area, no components were found on the ground.
"During the search, it was found that parts of the aircraft were not found elsewhere, so the aircraft crashed into the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, meeting all the requirements for passenger transportation.
The terrain shows a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get results as quickly as possible.
Gilberto López Meyer, director general of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was moving at cruise speed and the crash occurred on a soft rising terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the crash it was a normal overflight operation," he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome outlined six key points of the investigation:
Visual Flight :
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the ground during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at the start, according to which the aircraft is advancing towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico were noticeable layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes :
It is likely that due to the clouds the crew sought a lower area and greater visibility up to the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disturbance of the flight trajectory before the impact.
Dispersion of aircraft remnants on a limited territory:
The information we currently have at our disposal allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The drawing of the dispersal of the aircraft remains indicates that at the time of the impact on land the helicopter was holistic.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident that suggested there was an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with the land.
During field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain swings, the altitude of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
Photographs show footage, which is likely to have resulted in a breakdown along the mentioned route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After careful searches around the accident, no remains of the helicopter were found in a territory wider than the area of excavation, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still integral.
Mexican Institute of Health Insurance launches research into the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to uncover the gene causing obesity in children and young people.
In a report, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without permission, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in the Valle de México, where youth tests will be carried out from 8 a.m. every council.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and since October 8, this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children is collected, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
Every Saturday, anthropometric measurements are performed to all participants (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined, and genes are examined (they try to identify the genes involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects healthcare professionals’ concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
“Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years only, there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys and 47% in girls.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the country’s population differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally speaking, obesity genetics is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants was that they were given an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thereby determining whether they showed any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and elbow indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes conditions.
The information is confidential so far, doctors forward it in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to avoid their children from getting sick.
Cruz López explained that there are three main ingredients that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, day-to-day sitting in front of television, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also caused by high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic load that is the subject of this research.
There will be no asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalt with polymers to create a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climate conditions and temperature.
If the flooring was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair 200,000 dams after every rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Region, Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, said, adding that if the design and maintenance of the asphalt flooring were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in dams, or even it would be possible to completely remove them.
In his lecture Technological Cause of Moles, which he delivered within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalt with polymers, thereby creating a mixture having similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a group of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight called asphalt, and other low molecular weight called malt.
The visco-elastic character of asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures it tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but varies during the day depending on weather conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering expert noted.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tiles made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers there is an asphalt insert, formed by small stones poured into asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the insert is covered with asphalt.
When passing by cars or creating pressure, it is so possible that the forces in the tile are well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, it would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer, called a coat, will be placed on the asphalt insert, formed by fine stones, i.e. sand also poured into asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle racks, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since it will be exposed to a large load as part of the flooring, the coat must have a sufficient thickness and must pay attention to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind.
Once the terrain is moist, the water spreads inside and is difficult to get out, this causes the softening of all layers of the tiles and thus the formation of moulds.
He explained that during the creation of moulds, the coat film is first destroyed and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. Damage does not occur in one moment, but it is a slow process that should be stopped at the first signs using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of moulds, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tiles must correspond to the load of vehicles and must be guaranteed that this load is not exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that as far as the asphalt is concerned, we still have a lot of work to do and the research is at the beginning.It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow for easy repairs without having to use high temperatures.
