The Golden Rule of Balanced Budget
The government of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write the "golden rule" of fiscal policy into the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and avoid a possible downgrade of the Austrian rating agencies (AAA).
It was the Social-Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of the ministerial meeting in a situation where the Austrian public debt is with its 74.6% high above the maximum criterion of 60% set by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency was reduced by just one single degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more on interest each year,” said Christian Democratic Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus follows the request of the eurozone summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where heads of state and government strongly called for the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of balance of public accounts to be entered into a constitution or law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to decrease annually by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP), and starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP annually, while the federal states, as well as municipalities, will have to report a balanced budget.
The objective is to bring the public debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
