Energy Policy :
Facts must overcome dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balances or under emotions, then it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural for an election meeting to be an opportunity to reflect on such deposits and a place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
There are currently 7 billion people on the planet, but demographic developments will cause the demand for electricity to double by 2050 unless we want to deprive a significant part of the world’s population of vital components of life.
At the same time, the shortage of fossil fuels will need to be addressed in order to continue to produce electricity, while not forgetting the necessary need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a topic that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
This is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
But this is not the case for Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find some other resource capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which considers it right to build only the latest generation of power plants.
On the contrary, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name at least some countries, are continuing with determination in their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by resuming the construction of one of the power plants interrupted after the Three Mile Island power plant crash.
If the German model based on renewable energy is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts it.
Berlin’s choice will be reflected in higher electricity prices, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, and a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European champion in wind turbines, from which it takes 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to the irregularity of the wind, which makes the CO2 emissions and prices of Danish electricity higher by 65% and 50% respectively than the European average.
On the contrary, due to our unchanging energy policy, our neighbors will pay 40% more for electricity than the French households pay.
While in a globalized economy, energy costs are a key competitive factor and a guarantee ofining industry on the national territory, French enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
The price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay as well as fundamentally do not stand against this energy, as polls show.
Recall that our country’s energy policy has enabled us to build an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 follow-up jobs.
The highly exporting sector is being followed by a large number of specialized SMEs to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France decided to leave the core, it would sacrifice a significant number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose 6 billion euros a year, which the country earns from exporting nuclear equipment and services.
Which power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to run for 60 years while its manufacturer’s bankruptcy was planned?
In solving the energy equation, it is necessary to admit that there is no magic source for the production of energy, even that there is no evil source.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable energy plants by the French industrial group AREVA demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is imperative to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a National Nuclear Safety Authority, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of a new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognised, have the idea of safety in their blood.
