Nord Stream, the new port for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline linking Eastern Europe directly to Russia and run along the bottom of the Baltic Sea has begun to work.
It will have to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to properly celebrate this event.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream on Tuesday, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte jointly turned around the control valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Through this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will flow to Western Europe each year through the first 1.224-kilometer pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the state of Mecklenburg-Pommern.
The second pipeline, which is to be completed by the end of 2012, will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is equivalent to the total French consumption.
There is a possibility to build a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries have protested.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being passed by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
All at once, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats of blocking access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
I think this is a politically sensitive topic.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But it’s at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project has created cracks between Europeans from the East and the West.
Only five years ago, Russia managed to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and wealthy Western countries with high gas consumption, whose deposits are coming to an end.
“This gas pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us,” Fillon said at the opening ceremony, demonstrating how big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a significant technical act.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel with a concrete coat to protect it from marine vessels' anchors.
It lies on the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 meters.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid mines from the time of World War II.
“For safety reasons, a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures should be taken to protect flora and fauna.
The pipeline itself is a long metal serpent weighing as much as 242 Eiffel beams, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations anywhere in its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project managers rejected it when the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently settle off their coast.
"In the event of a failure, we will stop the passage of gas in less than 1 minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline leaks into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since the welding was designed to produce a leakage once every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline from the outside is carried out by a submarine robot pulled by a ship, while the interior of the pipeline is controlled by the device that circulates inside.
This cigar shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and is pressed with gas.
During the entire three-day journey at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts.
The gas pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without the need for any repairs.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom holds a 51 percent stake.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all of its gas transmission capacity to the company for a five-year contract, which can be renewed.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The construction of the pipeline was financed by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom will bear the risk.
The pipeline runs out of the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves with a height of 4.5 meters form the exit gate of the gas.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, this will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - Brand Notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded 50 years ago, wants to provide the joy of writing again.
It brings the smell of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its white-colored leaves that seem to have aged over time.
Moleskine, as we know him today, was born in 1997.
At the time, the Italian company Modo Modo based in Milan decided to launch a new design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes on the launch of a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (imitation of the skin), which is used for the surface of the benches, for example.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has restored popularity to an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from the covert production of the first years, when only 3,000 notes were made.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to assemble any artificial portrait of the buyer, as the notebook will fascinate the businessman just as much as the student or the professionals.
The image of the Moleskine notebook includes that its owners are people of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open spirit.
The small Italian company, which originally had 12 employees, now has 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notes to bookstores and through the FNAC store chain to small boutiques in the city centers, where he was able to promote his identity.
"We followed the spirit of the time and this need for new writing, despite the stormy development of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition" Treatment", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also unveiled new records of the notebook reminiscent of a leopard.
Moleskine benefits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop case ... The brand is expanding to a wide range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed people?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
Today is the 15th week of employment for disabled people.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is still twice the average, 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it embarrassing?
"No, emphasizes Éric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Week for Disabled Employment."
"The progress achieved in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the percentage of unemployed was not twice, but three times higher."
“H, there is still a lot to be done.”
It should be said that there are still numerous obstacles to unemployed persons with disabilities before they enter work.
These are older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a graduate degree and of the 2.3 million college students, only 10,000 are disabled.
And lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the handicapped versus 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that especially complicate the return to employment and which are “the core of the problem,” according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, which was founded in 1992 to help recruit disabled workers.
So much for the brakes.
There are still unspoken, ways of thinking that are developing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association found that surveyed managers have “a weak level of knowledge about disabled people” with “an exaggerated idea of people in the wheelchair and psychological or mental disabilities.”
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, dated from 2008, indicate a figure of 2.6%.
"We're now moving around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of the Agefiph organization tasked with collecting fees from that don't comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of "bounded" companies, as well as the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, which fell from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law that increased contributions created a strong pressure on, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
